Interface RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow<TVal,TPre,TSelf extends RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow<TVal,TPre,TSelf>>

  • Type Parameters:
    TVal - Value type of the repository.

    public static interface RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow<TVal,TPre,TSelf extends RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow<TVal,TPre,TSelf>>
    Compiler state allowing to specify the final synchronous steps of the data processing flow.

      • attemptGetFrom

        <TCur> RepositoryCompilerStates.RTermination<TVal,java.lang.Throwable,? extends RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow<TVal,TCur,?>> attemptGetFrom(Supplier<Result<TCur>> attemptSupplier)
        Like getFrom(com.google.android.agera.Supplier<TCur>), ignore the input value and attempt to get the new value from the given supplier. If the attempt fails, terminate the data processing flow by sending the failure to the termination clause that follows; otherwise take the successful value as the output of this directive.

      • attemptMergeIn

        <TAdd,TCur> RepositoryCompilerStates.RTermination<TVal,java.lang.Throwable,? extends RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow<TVal,TCur,?>> attemptMergeIn(Supplier<TAdd> supplier,
                                                                                                                                                     Merger<? super TPre,? super TAdd,Result<TCur>> attemptMerger)
        Like mergeIn(com.google.android.agera.Supplier<TAdd>, com.google.android.agera.Merger<? super TPre, ? super TAdd, TCur>), take the input value and the value newly obtained from the given supplier, and attempt to merge them using the given merger. If the attempt fails, terminate the data processing flow by sending the failure to the termination clause that follows; otherwise take the successful value as the output of this directive.

        This method is agnostic of the return type of the supplier. If it itself is fallible, the merger is held responsible for processing the failure, which may choose to pass the failure on as the result of the merge.

                                                                      Predicate<? super TCase> casePredicate)
        Use the case-function to compute a case value out of the input value and check it with the given predicate. If the predicate applies to the case value, continue the data processing flow with the input value, otherwise terminate the flow with the termination clause that follows. The termination clause takes the case value as its input.

      • sendTo

        TSelf sendTo(Receiver<? super TPre> receiver)
        Send the input value to the given receiver, and then pass on the input value as the output of this directive, not modifying it.

        Typical uses of this directive include reporting progress and/or errors in the UI, starting a side process, logging, profiling and debugging, etc. The Receiver.accept(T) method is called synchronously, which means its execution blocks the rest of the data processing flow. If the flow is to cancel with the interrupt signal, the receiver may also see the signal.

        The receiver does not have to use the input value, but if it does and it moves onto a different thread for processing the input value, note that the data processing flow does not guarantee value immutability or concurrent access for this receiver. For this reason, for a UI-calling receiver invoked from a background thread, implementation should extract any necessary data from the input value, and post the immutable form of it to the main thread for the UI calls, so the UI modifications are main-thread-safe while the data processing flow can continue concurrently.

        Note that the blocking semantics of this directive should not be taken as the permission to mutate the input in a way that affects the rest of the flow -- the appropriate directive for that purpose is transform, with a function that returns the same input instance after mutation.

      • bindWith

        <TAdd> TSelf bindWith(Supplier<TAdd> secondValueSupplier,
                      Binder<? super TPre,? super TAdd> binder)
        Send the input value and the value from the given supplier to the given binder, and then pass on the input value as the output of this directive, not modifying it.

        The same usage notes for sendTo(com.google.android.agera.Receiver<? super TPre>) apply to this directive.
